<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-203-289 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 453 461</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  March 11 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>European Community to investigate Korean chip dumping.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jones, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Semiconductor industryForeign CompetitionEuropeKoreaInternational TradeDRAMInvestigations.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>EUROPEAN COMMUNITY TO INVESTIGATE KOREAN CHIP DUMPING 03/11/91 BRUSSELS,BELGIUM, 1991 MAR 11 (NB) -- The Commission of the European Community, theEuropean Community's executive arm, acting on a complaint from the EuropeanElectronic Component Manufacturers Association, has opened an inquiry intothe alleged dumping of semiconductor chips onto the Western European marketby South Korea.andM;The association's complaint concerns imports of cut-price dynamic randomaccess memories (DRAM) - an essential semiconductor component of computermemories.andP;  Citing one example, the association said imports of one-megabyteDRAMs from South Korea had multiplied 13 times from 300,000 units in 1988 tofour million in 1989, with a resultant increase in market share from 1.43 to7.55 percent.andM;European manufacturers have increased their share of the DRAM market since ananti-dumping accord was signed with Japan early last year.andP;  But theassociation said much of the benefit had been lost to the South Koreanimports.andM;The complaint was made on behalf of Siemens, SGS-Thomson, and Motorola, andnamed Korean companies Samsung, Goldstar, Hyundai and Intel.andP;  The associationsaid the Korean manufacturers possessed a production capacity which wasconsiderably beyond the needs of their domestic market, and had established asales network within the EC to handle &quot;enormous quantities&quot; of the DRAMsemiconductors.andM;(Peter Jones/19910311)</TEXT></DOC>